---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import d from '../data/site_data.json';
import { pct, frac, fold, count, short, cellType } from '../lib/fmt.js';

const title = 'Dual-marker discovery — combinatorial surface targets in prostate cancer';
const description =
  'A per-patient single-cell scan for pairs of surface markers a logic-gated therapy could use to hit prostate cancer and spare healthy tissue, anchored on recovery of the PSMA-PSCA benchmark.';

const folh1 = d.control.find((c) => c.entity.startsWith('FOLH1 (single)'));
const psca = d.control.find((c) => c.entity.startsWith('PSCA (single)'));
const gate = d.control.find((c) => c.kind === 'AND_pair');
const n = d.nominated;
const nFrontier = d.surface_frontier.length;
---
<Base title={title} description={description} page="home">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Built with Claude: Life Sciences hackathon<br />Research track · 2026</p>
      <h1>Two antigens that are each unsafe alone become selective when a therapy requires both.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        PSMA is detected in {pct(folh1.worst_healthy_xprostate)} of cells in the worst healthy tissue it
        touches. PSCA reaches {pct(psca.worst_healthy_xprostate)}. Requiring <b>both</b> at once brings the
        worst extra-prostatic co-detection down to {pct(gate.worst_healthy_xprostate)}. That collapse is
        the rationale behind the split-signal CAR, and this scan reproduces it from single-cell data
        alone. Recovering it is what earns the ranking behind it the right to be read.
      </p>
      <div class="btnrow">
        <a class="btn primary" href="/explore">Explore with Claude &rarr;</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/report">Read the report</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/challenge">The data and the method</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats">
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="n">{frac(gate.worst_healthy_xprostate)}</div>
          <div class="l">worst extra-prostatic co-detection of the PSMA-PSCA AND gate, from {frac(psca.worst_healthy_xprostate)} for PSCA alone</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="n">{d.study.n_patients_scored}</div>
          <div class="l">patients, each scored on their own cells, so no one donor can carry a pair</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="n">{short(d.study.n_healthy_cells)}</div>
          <div class="l">healthy cells, {d.study.n_healthy_celltypes} cell types across {d.study.n_healthy_tissues} tissues, as the safety denominator</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="n">{d.study.n_panel_genes_scanned}</div>
          <div class="l">curated surface markers scanned, every pair, under both gate logics</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>The problem</h2>
      <p>
        Few surface antigens are truly absent from every healthy tissue. That is why single-antigen
        CAR-T, T-cell engagers, and antibody-drug conjugates struggle in solid tumors: the antigen that
        marks the cancer also marks something you cannot afford to destroy. The toxicity is on target. It
        is the target that is the problem.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logic-gated targeting requires two conditions before a cell is engaged, which can recover the
        missing specificity. An <b>AND gate</b> engages only a cell carrying both markers. A
        <b>NOT gate</b> engages on an activator unless a blocker marks the cell as healthy, and it is
        directional: swapping the two markers is a different hypothesis, not the same one.
      </p>

      <h2>The benchmark</h2>
      <p>
        PSMA (FOLH1) and PSCA are a preclinically validated split-signal CAR pair. If the scoring is
        sound, it should reproduce the reason why. It does. Each antigen alone is broadly detected
        outside the prostate, and requiring both collapses the worst case:
      </p>

      <div class="tw">
        <table class="fig">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Requirement</th>
              <th class="num">Malignant coverage<br /><span class="sub">median across patients</span></th>
              <th class="num">Worst healthy tissue<br /><span class="sub">outside the prostate</span></th>
              <th>Where that liability sits</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {d.control.map((c) => (
              <tr class={c.kind === 'AND_pair' ? 'lead' : undefined}>
                <td><b>{c.entity.replace('FOLH1', 'PSMA').replace(' (single)', ' alone')}</b></td>
                <td class="num">{frac(c.tumor_median)}</td>
                <td class="num">{frac(c.worst_healthy_xprostate)}</td>
                <td class="ct">{cellType(c.worst_xp_celltype)}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <p>
          <b>Read this as a trust signal, not a discovery.</b> The recovery is a safety collapse, not a
          coverage result: the gate's own malignant coverage is low ({frac(gate.tumor_median)}), because
          PSCA transcript is dropout-prone. The panel contained the known pair and the analysis was not
          preregistered, so this is not a blind rediscovery. Against
          {' '}{d.negative_control.n_random_pairs} random surface pairs, the benchmark is more selective
          than {pct(d.negative_control.frac_random_pairs_worse)} of them, which the report calls a weak
          signal and a sanity check rather than proof of specificity: a pair can also look clean simply by
          covering very little tumor.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>The nominated pair</h2>
      <p>
        With the benchmark reproduced, the same scoring ranks the surface-accessible pairs on a Pareto
        frontier of per-patient coverage floor against worst-case healthy liability.
        {' '}<b>{nFrontier} clean pairs</b> sit on that frontier. The one carried forward is
        {' '}<b>{n.pair.replace('FOLH1', 'PSMA').replace(' + ', ' × ')}</b>, an AND gate, and it is worth
        being precise about why: it is not the highest-coverage pair on the frontier, nor the lowest-risk.
        It is the frontier pair with the lowest liability among those with substantial coverage, and it
        was chosen for the headline because <b>both antigens already have clinical-grade binders</b>. That
        is a translational judgement laid on top of the frontier, not the output of an optimizer.
      </p>

      <div class="tw">
        <table class="fig">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>What</th><th class="num">Value</th><th>Read it as</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Malignant coverage, median across patients</td>
              <td class="num">{frac(n.tumor_median)}</td>
              <td>{fold(n.coverage_fold_vs_psma_psca)} the benchmark's median co-detection, and only that. Not {fold(n.coverage_fold_vs_psma_psca)} better</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Coverage floor, lower decile across patients</td>
              <td class="num">{frac(n.tumor_q10)}</td>
              <td>indicative, not precise: the bootstrap interval over patients is wide</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="lead">
              <td>Worst healthy tissue outside the prostate</td>
              <td class="num">{frac(n.worst_healthy_xprostate)}</td>
              <td>{cellType(n.worst_xp_celltype)}. Comparable to the benchmark's {frac(gate.worst_healthy_xprostate)}, and marginally worse, not better</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Malignant minus matched benign prostate</td>
              <td class="num">{frac(n.malignant_vs_benign)}</td>
              <td>it marks the cancer, not the whole gland</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        Each marker alone is far more exposed: PSMA reaches {frac(n.single_a_worst_xp)} and STEAP1
        {' '}{frac(n.single_b_worst_xp)} in their own worst healthy tissue. The gate is what buys the
        selectivity. But a median coverage of {frac(n.tumor_median)} is not obviously adequate for
        monotherapy, and whether the residual liability is clinically acceptable cannot be judged from
        transcript data at all.
      </p>

      <h2>What this is not</h2>
      <div class="callout result">
        <p>
          <b>The pair is not the contribution, and it is not novel.</b> A dual PSMA/STEAP1
          antibody-drug conjugate (ABBV-969) is already in phase 1, though it binds either antigen, so it
          is OR-like rather than a strict AND gate. What is offered here is the AND framing and the
          scoring underneath it: per-patient rather than pooled, against a matched benign-prostate control
          and an assay-matched, donor-robust healthy reference, with the benchmark reproduced before any
          new pair is nominated.
        </p>
      </div>
      <p>
        These are <b>transcript-level, hypothesis-generating rankings, not evidence of therapeutic
        safety</b>. Single-cell RNA measures mRNA, not surface antigen density, epitope availability,
        binding, or shedding. Same-cell surface co-expression needs CITE-seq, multiplex IHC, or
        dual-colour flow to confirm, and none of that was done here.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <b>NOT gates are a negative result</b>. No activator-blocker combination in the panel achieved
        both high malignant coverage and low normal-tissue escape, and the blocker-negative call depends
        on trusting single-cell dropout. It is reported as a negative result rather than quietly dropped.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <a href="/report">report states every limitation in full</a> and does not soften them, starting
        with the fact that the cohort's own malignant label is built from expression signatures, and that
        this is one cohort of localised, hormone-naive disease.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="cards">
        <a class="card" href="/challenge">
          <span class="k">The setup</span>
          <h3>Challenge &amp; data</h3>
          <p>The biological problem, the atlases, and how a pair is actually scored.</p>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="/claude">
          <span class="k">The process</span>
          <h3>How I used Claude</h3>
          <p>What Claude built, what it caught, what it was overruled on, and what it retracted.</p>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="/report">
          <span class="k">The science</span>
          <h3>The report</h3>
          <p>Abstract, methods, results, and the limitations stated plainly.</p>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="/explore">
          <span class="k">The tool</span>
          <h3>Explore with Claude</h3>
          <p>Browse the ranked pairs and ask a grounded Claude agent about any of them.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
